Now I have the full picture. Here's the formal audit against the testsmells.org 19-smell catalog.

---

## Test Smell Audit — `UserRepositoryIntegrationTests.cs`

**Framework:** MSTest v4 · **Scope:** Integration tests (`[TestCategory("Integration")]`) · **Catalog:** testsmells.org 19-smell taxonomy

### Summary Dashboard

| Severity | Smell Count | Affected Tests |
|----------|-------------|----------------|
| High     | 3           | 3              |
| Medium   | 1           | 1              |
| Low      | 0           | 0              |
| **Total**| **4**       | **4** of 7     |

### Smells Not Detected (15 of 19 — Clean)

Mystery Guest, Eager Test, Magic Number Test, Sensitive Equality, Exception Handling, General Fixture, Ignored Test, Duplicate Assert, Lazy Test, Constructor Initialization, Default Test, Redundant Print, Redundant Assertion, Resource Optimism, Empty Test.

**Calibration note:** Mystery Guest and Eager Test were evaluated but _downgraded to clean_ because this is a `[TestCategory("Integration")]` class. The in-memory SQLite connection is a test double (not a real external resource), and multi-method call sequences are appropriate for integration-level verification.

---

### HIGH Severity Findings

#### ① Sleepy Test (Smell #3)

**Test:** `NotifyOnInsert_SendsEventAfterDelay` (line 87)
**Research:** Camara et al. (SAST 2021) — correlated with flaky test failures.
**Integration calibration:** Still HIGH even for integration tests. Sleep-based waits are non-deterministic at any level.

```csharp
// ❌ Current — hard 3-second wall-clock wait
Thread.Sleep(3000);
Assert.IsTrue(_repository.WasNotificationSent(user.Id));
```

**Fix — poll with timeout:**
```csharp
// ✅ Deterministic polling with bounded wait
var timeout = TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5);
var sw = Stopwatch.StartNew();
while (sw.Elapsed < timeout)
{
    if (_repository.WasNotificationSent(user.Id))
        return; // pass
    await Task.Delay(50);
}
Assert.Fail("Notification was not sent within timeout.");
```
**Risk if unfixed:** Flaky CI failures on slow agents; wastes 3s per run unconditionally.

---

#### ② Conditional Test Logic (Smell #1)

**Test:** `GetUser_ReturnsCorrectType` (lines 101–108)
**Research:** Spadini et al. (MSR 2020) — consistently rated serious by developers.

```csharp
// ❌ Current — one branch may never execute
if (loaded is PremiumUser premium)
{
    Assert.IsTrue(premium.DiscountRate > 0);
}
else
{
    Assert.AreEqual("Eve", loaded!.Name);
}
```

**Fix — split into two explicit tests:**
```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetUser_StandardUser_ReturnsName()
{
    _repository.Insert(new User("eve@example.com", "Eve"));
    var loaded = _repository.GetByEmail("eve@example.com");
    Assert.IsNotNull(loaded);
    Assert.AreEqual("Eve", loaded.Name);
}

[TestMethod]
public void GetUser_PremiumUser_HasDiscountRate()
{
    _repository.Insert(new PremiumUser("eve@example.com", "Eve", discountRate: 0.1m));
    var loaded = (PremiumUser)_repository.GetByEmail("eve@example.com")!;
    Assert.IsTrue(loaded.DiscountRate > 0);
}
```
**Risk if unfixed:** The `PremiumUser` branch silently never runs if `Insert` always creates a standard user — hidden gap in test coverage.

---

#### ③ Assertion-Free Test / Unknown Test (Smell #4)

**Test:** `BulkInsert_RunsWithoutErrors` (lines 113–119)

```csharp
// ❌ Current — no assertion; passes even if every insert silently fails
for (int i = 0; i < 100; i++)
{
    _repository.Insert(new User($"bulk{i}@example.com", $"Bulk User {i}"));
}
```

The name implies "no-exception" intent, but the test provides **zero verification** that rows were persisted.

**Fix — assert the observable outcome:**
```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void BulkInsert_PersistsAllRecords()
{
    for (int i = 0; i < 100; i++)
    {
        _repository.Insert(new User($"bulk{i}@example.com", $"Bulk User {i}"));
    }

    var users = _repository.ListAll();
    Assert.AreEqual(100, users.Count);
}
```
**Risk if unfixed:** False confidence — the test contributes to coverage metrics while verifying nothing.

---

### MEDIUM Severity Findings

#### ④ Assertion Roulette (Extended Smell)

**Test:** `InsertUser_PersistsToDatabase` (lines 35–38)
**Threshold:** 3+ assertions without message parameters (this test has 4).
**Research:** Peruma et al. (CASCON 2019) — most prevalent smell across OSS projects.

```csharp
// ❌ Current — when one fails, which property was wrong?
Assert.IsNotNull(loaded);
Assert.AreEqual("Alice", loaded.Name);
Assert.AreEqual("alice@example.com", loaded.Email);
Assert.IsTrue(loaded.Id > 0);
```

**Fix — add diagnostic messages:**
```csharp
Assert.IsNotNull(loaded, "User should be retrievable after insert");
Assert.AreEqual("Alice", loaded.Name, "Name should round-trip");
Assert.AreEqual("alice@example.com", loaded.Email, "Email should round-trip");
Assert.IsTrue(loaded.Id > 0, "Database should assign a positive ID");
```
**Risk if unfixed:** CI failure logs show only `Assert.AreEqual failed` with no context, slowing triage.

---

### Well-Written Tests (Smell-Free) ✅

| Test | Notes |
|------|-------|
| `UpdateUser_ModifiesExistingRecord` | Clear arrange-act-assert, focused assertions |
| `DeleteUser_RemovesFromDatabase` | Single assertion, tests the absence correctly |
| `ListUsers_ReturnsAllInserted` | Count contextually obvious (3 inserts → 3 count), `CollectionAssert` used |
| `InsertUser_ConcurrentInserts_MaintainsIntegrity` | Appropriate use of `Task.WhenAll` with a concrete assertion |

---

### Prioritized Remediation Plan

| Priority | Smell | Fix | Impact |
|----------|-------|-----|--------|
| 1 | **Assertion-Free Test** | Add `Assert.AreEqual(100, ...)` | Eliminates false-pass risk |
| 2 | **Conditional Test Logic** | Split into 2 tests | Exposes hidden coverage gap |
| 3 | **Sleepy Test** | Replace `Thread.Sleep` with poll loop | Removes flakiness + saves 3s |
| 4 | **Assertion Roulette** | Add message parameters | Improves failure diagnostics |

**Bottom line:** 4 of 7 tests carry a cataloged smell — but the fixes are all straightforward. The remaining 3 tests are clean and follow good integration-test patterns. This is a solid foundation that needs targeted cleanup, not a rewrite.
